    <para id="id1164406693644">= <figure id="id1164448903520"><media id="id1164448903520_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics12-1a89.png" id="id1164448903520__onlineimage" height="48" width="77"/></media></figure> = <figure id="id1164406210828"><media id="id1164406210828_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics13-1c46.png" id="id1164406210828__onlineimage" height="42" width="78"/></media></figure> = 63.4</para>
    <para id="id1164449789092">Internal Voltage Gain = <figure id="id1997312"><media id="id1997312_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics14-3134.png" id="id1997312__onlineimage" height="48" width="165"/></media></figure> .</para>
    <para id="id1164421184648">Note these are non-inverting gains.</para>
    <para id="id1164403602119">In the lab, we will get vastly different gains by including source resistance and neglecting source resistance. So while making voltage gain measurement we have to be careful as to which gain we are measuring.</para>
